Feature Selection for Correlation Analysis¶

The following features selected for correlation analysis were chosen based on their direct impact on ticket sales and, consequently, total revenue. Understanding the relationships between these features and ticket sales is crucial for optimizing revenue and improving forecasting accuracy.

In [255]:
features_for_correlation = ['film_code', 'cinema_code', 'show_time', 'month', 'quarter', 'day', 'total_sales']
        
        correlation_matrix = df[features_for_correlation].corr()
        
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
        sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f")
        plt.title('Correlation Heatmap of Selected Features')
        plt.show()
Month and Quarter: These are linked to the film_code, meaning some films are released more often in certain months or quarters.¶
Showtime: This is closely linked to total_sales. Films shown at certain times, like evenings, usually sell more tickets.¶
Film Code: This is also closely linked to total_sales. Popular films tend to make more money.¶
Least Correlated: Showtime and cinema_code are the least connected. The time a film is shown doesn't strongly depend on which cinema it's in.¶

def remove_outliers(df, column):
            Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
            Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
            IQR = Q3 - Q1
            lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
            upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
            return df[(df[column] >= lower_bound) & (df[column] <= upper_bound)]
        
        column_outliers = ['Adj Close', 'Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Close', 'Volume'] 
        
        for column in column_outliers:
            df = remove_outliers(df, column)
        
        # Check if outliers are removed
        plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
        plt.boxplot(df[column_outliers])
        plt.title('Box Plot of Columns after Removing Outliers')
        plt.xticks(range(1, len(column_outliers) + 1), column_outliers, rotation=45)
        plt.ylabel('Values')
        plt.show()

Modeling for Historical Stock Price Analysis¶

In [127]:
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
        train_data = df.set_index('Date')
        
        arima_model = ARIMA(train_data['Adj Close'], order=(5, 1, 0))
        arima_result = arima_model.fit()
        arima_predictions = arima_result.predict(typ='levels')
In [128]:
comparison_df = pd.DataFrame({'Date': train_data.index, 'Actual': train_data['Adj Close'], 'Predicted': arima_predictions})
        comparison_df['Predicted'] = comparison_df['Predicted'].shift(-1)
        
        # The predicted row has an erroneous number in the first row and the actual prediction begins in the 2nd row
        #The erroneous 0.0000 in the first row will be removed.
        comparison_df = comparison_df[:-1]
        
        # The models prediction will be tested against the actual dataset to see if it predicts accurately and can therefore be trusted.
        print("Actual vs Corrected Predicted for Current Data:")
        comparison_df.head()

forecast_horizon = 30
        arima_forecast = arima_result.forecast(steps=forecast_horizon)
        
        last_date = train_data.index[-1]
        forecast_dates = pd.date_range(start=last_date, periods=forecast_horizon + 1)
        
        forecast_df = pd.DataFrame({'Date': forecast_dates[1:], 'Forecasted': arima_forecast})
